from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from tqdm import tqdm  # Import tqdm

range_n_clusters = list(range(1, 10))
wcss_values = []

# Use tqdm to wrap around your range to provide a progress bar
for n_clusters in tqdm(range_n_clusters, desc="Processing clusters"):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(df_num)

    wcss = kmeans.inertia_
    wcss_values.append(wcss)

# Plot the WCSS values for different numbers of clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.plot(range_n_clusters, wcss_values, marker='o', linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('WCSS')
plt.title('WCSS vs. Number of Clusters')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

2.3 Accuracy of Kmeans Model¶

Davies Bouldin Score

In [ ]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import davies_bouldin_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming df_num is your DataFrame
# Create a list to store Davies-Bouldin scores
dbi_scores = []

# Loop over different values of k
for k in range(1, 11):
    # Apply KMeans
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    cluster_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(df_num)

    # Calculate Davies-Bouldin Index
    # Skip the calculation for k = 1 as it's not defined for a single cluster
    if k > 1:
        dbi_score = davies_bouldin_score(df_num, cluster_labels)
        dbi_scores.append(dbi_score)
    else:
        dbi_scores.append(None)

# Plotting the Davies-Bouldin scores
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(range(1, 11), dbi_scores, marker='o')
plt.title('Davies-Bouldin Index for Different Numbers of Clusters')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Davies-Bouldin Index')
plt.xticks(range(1, 11))  # Set x-axis ticks for each number of clusters
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Inertia can be obtained directly from the KMeans object
inertia = kmeans.inertia_

# Silhouette Score requires the original data and the cluster labels
silhouette = silhouette_score(df_num, df_num['Cluster'])

print(f'Inertia of the KMeans model: {inertia}')
print(f'Silhouette Score of the KMeans model: {silhouette}')

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.gridspec as gridspec

# Selected columns
selected_columns = [
    'Ratio_MedRPP_Low',
    'Ratio_MedRPP_Below Average',
    'Ratio_MedRPP_Average',
    'Ratio_MedRPP_Above Average',
    'Ratio_MedRPP_High'
]

# Color palette
colors = [
    'blue',
    'lightblue',
    'lightgrey',
    'lightcoral',
    'red']

# Extracting only the selected columns from the average_per_cluster DataFrame
subset_data = average_per_cluster[selected_columns]

# Create a gridspec layout with 2 rows and 3 columns
# Last column (3rd column) is for the legend
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
gs = gridspec.GridSpec(2, 3, width_ratios=[1, 1, 0.1], height_ratios=[1, 1])

# Plot pie charts in the first two columns of the grid
for cluster in range(4):
    ax = fig.add_subplot(gs[cluster//2, cluster%2])  # Cluster//2 defines the row, cluster%2 defines the column
    ax.pie(subset_data.iloc[cluster], labels=selected_columns, autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=50, colors=colors)
    ax.axis('equal')
    ax.set_title(f'Cluster {cluster + 1}')

# Create legend in the last column of the grid
ax_legend = fig.add_subplot(gs[:, 2])  # Span across all rows
patches = [plt.plot([], [], marker="o", ms=10, ls="", mec=None, color=colors[i],
            label="{:s}".format(selected_columns[i]))[0] for i in range(len(selected_columns))]
ax_legend.legend(handles=patches, loc='center', ncol=1)
ax_legend.axis('off')

plt.suptitle('Distribution of DiffMedRPP columns for each Cluster')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

4.5 Travelling Purpose Pies¶

In [ ]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

selected_columns = [
    'Travelling_Purpose_BLEISURE',
    'Travelling_Purpose_BUSINESS',
    'Travelling_Purpose_PERSONAL',
    'Travelling_Purpose_VACATION',
    'Travelling_Purpose_VFR']

colors = [
    'lightgrey',        # Less obvious for BLEISURE
    '#ff3333',          # More obvious red for BUSINESS
    'lightgrey',        # Less obvious for PERSONAL
    '#33cc33',          # More obvious green for VACATION
    '#1a75ff'           # More obvious blue for VFR
]

shortened_labels = [label.replace('Travelling_Purpose_', '') for label in selected_columns]

# Extracting only the selected columns from the average_per_cluster DataFrame
subset_data = average_per_cluster[selected_columns]
n_clusters = subset_data.shape[0]
n_categories = len(selected_columns)

# Create a bar chart for each cluster
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(16, 9))  # Create a 2x2 subplot grid
flat_axes = axes.flatten()  # Flatten the 2x2 array of Axes
# Set the positions and width for the bars
bar_positions = np.arange(n_categories)
bar_width = 0.5  # Adjust the width as needed
# Loop through each cluster and plot a bar chart
for cluster in range(n_clusters):
    cluster_data = subset_data.iloc[cluster]
    ax = flat_axes[cluster]
    ax.bar(bar_positions, cluster_data, bar_width, label=f'Cluster {cluster + 1}', color=colors)

    # Add some text for labels and title
    ax.set_title(f'Cluster {cluster + 1}',fontsize = 13)
    ax.set_xticks(bar_positions)
    ax.set_xticklabels(shortened_labels, rotation=0,fontsize = 13)
    ax.set_ylabel('Values')  # Replace 'Values' with a more appropriate label if needed

# Set a title for the entire figure
plt.suptitle('Distribution of Travelling Purpose columns for each Cluster')

# Add space between subplots to avoid label overlap
plt.tight_layout()

plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 8))

colors = ['lightpink', 'lightblue', 'lightgreen', 'lightgrey']  # Assuming 4 clusters

# Plot clusters
for i, color in enumerate(colors):
    indicesToKeep = principalDf['Cluster'] == i
    ax.scatter(principalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'PC1']
               , principalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'PC2']
               , c=color
               , s=10, label=f'Cluster {i+1}')

# Calculate centroids in the PCA space
# Assuming `kmeans` is your KMeans model and `pca` is your PCA object
centroids_pca = pca.transform(kmeans.cluster_centers_)

# Plot centroids
centroid_colors = ['darkred', 'darkblue', 'darkgreen', 'black']  # Different colors for centroids
for i, color in enumerate(centroid_colors):
    ax.scatter(centroids_pca[i, 0], centroids_pca[i, 1], c=color, marker='X', s=100, label=f'Centroid {i+1}')

ax.set_xlabel('Principal Component 1', fontsize=15)
ax.set_ylabel('Principal Component 2', fontsize=15)
ax.set_title('KMeans Clusters', fontsize=20)
ax.legend(loc='best')  # Add legend to distinguish centroids
ax.grid()
plt.show()
